        "at": "2026-07-18T19:46:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "act": "THE COUPLING",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Let a one-dimensional lattice repeat every a. At the first zone boundary, k equals plus or minus pi over a. A reciprocal-lattice kick connects those degenerate waves.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.37,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T19:46:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "The coupled waves form cosine-like and sine-like standing waves. One density peaks where this model places the attractive ion potential; the other peaks between those sites.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.22,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T19:46:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "act": "THE SPLIT",
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "In the nearly-free-electron approximation, those densities have different potential-energy averages. For a suitable phase convention, the levels shift down and up by the magnitude of the relevant Fourier coefficient.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.31,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T19:46:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "act": "THE GAP",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "So this two-state weak-potential model gives a zone-boundary gap of two times the magnitude of V G. Real crystals can have many orbitals, dimensions, and symmetries, so this is a mechanism, not a universal one-number recipe.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.65,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T19:46:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "act": "THE MATERIALS",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "A partially filled band usually supports metallic conduction. A completely filled valence band separated from empty states by a gap can describe an insulator or semiconductor; temperature, disorder, interactions, and topology add qualifications.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.66,
